Difference in performance of a new iteration approach



The first column of each table (infinite threshold) shows the current state of the performance (the threshold is infinite, so it's never reached and we never perform the second lookup to find the last element of the iteration and start comparing pointers instead of keys with tuples).

Each table has its own borders for specifying the color of a cell, but overall green cells show speed-ups and red ones show slowdowns.

The tests are performed on almost filled 3-level tree with hints.

The test script is found in the perf1.lua file in this repo.

The raw data is found in the perf1.data file in this repo.

sk2 (raw)



Measured the following:
1. Create an iterator by a non-unique key {0} (fieldno 2) and step the specified amount of times.
2. Do 1 until the amount of stepped tuples is 18000 (that's how much tuples is in index).

Optimization threshold is the step number after which the second lookup is performed to find the end of the iteration and we start to compare pointers instead of keys with tuples. For example, if threshold is 1, then the lookup is performed on the second step (so after 1 step).

Data: raw measured time in seconds Red: +5% (slower)
Green: -5% (faster)

sk2000



Measured the following:
1. Create an iterator by a non-unique key {0} (fieldno 2000) and step the specified amount of times.
2. Do 1 until the amount of stepped tuples is 18000 (that's how much tuples is in index).

Optimization threshold is the step number after which the second lookup is performed to find the end of the iteration and we start to compare pointers instead of keys with tuples. For example, if threshold is 1, then the lookup is performed on the second step (so after 1 step).

1. Create an iterator by a non-unique key {0} (fieldno 3000) and step the specified amount of times.

Optimization threshold is the step number after which the second lookup is performed to find the end of the iteration and we start to compare pointers instead of keys with tuples. For example, if threshold is 1, then the lookup is performed on the second step (so after 1 step).
